                                        <ol><h3 class="title">Notes</h3>
				
				<li class="footnote " id="-10411_000_021"><a name="-10411_000_021">&nbsp;</a>
					<span class="label"><a name="footnote1-10411_000_021">1.</a></span>
					<p>Kay&nbsp;S. Hymowitz, <span class="emphasis">Manning Up: How the Rise of Women Has Turned Men into Boys</span> (2011), 16.</p>
				</li>
				<li class="footnote " id="-10411_000_021"><a name="-10411_000_021">&nbsp;</a>
					<span class="label"><a name="footnote2-10411_000_021">2.</a></span>
					<p>&ldquo;When you ask young people today what will make them adults, almost no one mentions marriage. They are far more likely to see issues around work&mdash;completing education, financial independence, a full-time job&mdash;as the signs that they have arrived. Work, career, independence: these are the primary sources of identity today&rdquo; (Hymowitz, <span class="emphasis">Manning Up,</span> 45). The pressure on women to adopt this antimarriage ethic is especially intense. A <span class="emphasis">Times</span> of London contributor wrote: &ldquo;No one, not my family or my teachers, ever said, &lsquo;Oh yes, and by the way you might want to be a wife and mother too.&rsquo; They were so determined we would follow a new, egalitarian, modern path that the historic ambitions of generations of women&mdash;to get married and raise a family&mdash;were intentionally airbrushed from their vision of our future&rdquo; (Eleanor Mills, &ldquo;Learning to Be Left on the Shelf,&rdquo; <span class="emphasis">Sunday Times,</span> Apr. 18, 2010, www.thetimes.co.uk; in Hymowitz, <span class="emphasis">Manning Up,</span> 72). Another writer in her 40s quoted some responses to an article she wrote about her regrets over not marrying: &ldquo;I am totally appalled by your need for a man,&rdquo; &ldquo;Get some self-esteem!&rdquo; &ldquo;You have taken codependency to a whole new low,&rdquo; and &ldquo;If my daughter grows up to want a man half as much as you do, I will know that I&rsquo;ve done something wrong in raising her&rdquo; (Lori Gottlieb, <span class="emphasis">Marry Him: The Case for Settling for Mr. Good Enough</span> [2010], 55).</p>
					<p>The good news is that most people, including educated young adults, aren&rsquo;t buying the antimarriage, antifamily message. &ldquo;According to a study by a University of Pennsylvania economist, in the United States in 2008, 86 percent of college-educated white women were married by age 40, compared with 88 percent of those with less than a four-year degree. The numbers for white, college-educated men are similar: 84 percent of them were married by 40 in 2008. The conventional wisdom, not borne out by research, by the way, may have it that marriage is a raw deal for women. But college-educated white women don&rsquo;t seem to believe it. They are the most likely of any group to think that &lsquo;married people are generally happier than unmarried people.&rsquo; &hellip; The large majority&mdash;70 percent&mdash;of first-year college students think raising a family is &lsquo;essential&rsquo; or &lsquo;very important&rsquo; to their futures&rdquo; (Hymowitz, <span class="emphasis">Manning Up,</span> 173&ndash;74).</p>
				</li>
				<li class="footnote " id="-10411_000_021"><a name="-10411_000_021">&nbsp;</a>
					<span class="label"><a name="footnote3-10411_000_021">3.</a></span>
					<p>Philip&nbsp;G. Zimbardo and Nikita Duncan, <span class="emphasis">The Demise of Guys: Why Boys Are Struggling and What We Can Do about It</span> (2012), e-book; see the chapter &ldquo;Behind the Headlines.&rdquo;</p>
				</li>
				<li class="footnote " id="-10411_000_021"><a name="-10411_000_021">&nbsp;</a>
					<span class="label"><a name="footnote4-10411_000_021">4.</a></span>
					<p>Barbara Dafoe Whitehead, <span class="emphasis">Why There Are No Good Men Left: The Romantic Plight of the New Single Woman</span> (2003), 67.</p>
				</li>
				<li class="footnote " id="-10411_000_021"><a name="-10411_000_021">&nbsp;</a>
					<span class="label"><a name="footnote5-10411_000_021">5.</a></span>
					<p>Amanda Dickson, &ldquo;&lsquo;Hunger Games&rsquo; Main Character a Heroine for Our Day,&rdquo; <span class="emphasis">Deseret News,</span> Apr. 2, 2012, www.deseretnews.com.</p>
				</li>
				<li class="footnote " id="-10411_000_021"><a name="-10411_000_021">&nbsp;</a>
					<span class="label"><a name="footnote6-10411_000_021">6.</a></span>
					<p>Gordon&nbsp;B. Hinckley, &ldquo;Welfare Responsibilities of the Priesthood Quorums,&rdquo; <span class="emphasis">Ensign,</span> Nov. 1977, 86.</p>
				</li>
				<li class="footnote " id="-10411_000_021"><a name="-10411_000_021">&nbsp;</a>
